The probability that a single die is not greater than 4 is \( \frac{2}{3} \). - The probability that none of the four dice are greater than 4 is \( \left( \frac{2}{3} \right)^4 = \frac{16}{81} \). - Therefore, \( P(A) = 1 - \frac{16}{81} = \frac{65}{81} \). 2. **Calculate the probability that at least two dice are greater than 2 (event B):** - The probability that a single die is not greater than 2 is \( \frac{1}{3} \). - The probability that at most one die is greater than 2 is calculated using the binomial distribution: - \( P(\text{0 dice} > 2) = \left( \frac{2}{3} \right)^4 = \frac{16}{81} \) - \( P(\text{1 die} > 2) = \binom{4}{1} \left( \frac{1}{3} \right)^1 \left( \frac{2}{3} \right)^3 = \frac{32}{81} \) - Therefore, \( P(B) = 1 - \left( \frac{16}{81} + \frac{32}{81} \right) = \frac{11}{27} \). 3. **Calculate the probability that at least two dice are greater than 2 but none are greater than 4 (event B and not A):** - If all dice are ≤4, the probability that a die is ≥3 is \( \frac{1}{2} \). - The probability that at least two out of four dice are ≥3 is calculated using the binomial distribution: - \( P(\text{at least 2 dice} \geq 3 \mid \text{all dice} \leq 4) = 1 - \binom{4}{0} \left( \frac{1}{2} \right)^4 - \binom{4}{1} \left( \frac{1}{2} \right)^4 = \frac{11}{16} \) - The probability that all dice are ≤4 is \( \left( \frac{2}{3} \right)^4 = \frac{16}{81} \). - Therefore, \( P(B \text{ and not } A) = \frac{16}{81} \times \frac{11}{16} = \frac{11}{81} \). 4. **Calculate the probability that both events A and B occur:** - Using inclusion-exclusion: \( P(A \cap B) = P(B) - P(B \text{ and not } A) = \frac{11}{27} - \frac{11}{81} = \frac{22}{81} \). The final answer is \( 81 - 22 = \boxed{59} \).
